# Cybernet Hostname Variant Doctrine

When expanding a Cybernet hostname into AD discovery candidates, follow the bounded variant
doctrine. This is naming-doctrine fuzzing driven by known human mistakes, not generic fuzzy search.

Hard caps:

- No broad fuzzy AD search; generate candidates only from approved target manifests
  (`ExpectedSerial`, `ExpectedHostname`, `Site`).
- Do not query outside the bounded candidate set.
- An AD variant match is a discovery candidate only. It can never become serial-confirmed; serial
  proof requires a privileged identity check.
- WNH <-> WMH is a controlled site-affinity substitution, not a generic typo. If `Site` conflicts
  with the substituted prefix, classify as `ad_prefix_site_mismatch` + `needs_site_context_review`.
- Numeric block transposition is hard-bounded (adjacent single-swap only); discovery candidates only.
- Any multiple-match result stays review-required and never auto-resolves.
- Use transparency/scope-control language; this is not stealth, evasion, or log suppression.

Every emitted candidate must carry a confidence tier and a next action.

